1
00:00:01,988 --> 00:00:30,054
namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sambhudassa namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sambhudassa namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sambhudassa Homage to the Buddha, the Blessed, Noble and Fully Self-Enlightened One.

2
00:00:32,801 --> 00:00:48,853
I thought this evening just to let the mind wander a bit really about this whole business of goodwill since it's Christmas.

3
00:00:50,689 --> 00:00:54,637
So this was, if you remember, the message over the manger, wasn't it?

4
00:00:54,917 --> 00:00:58,804
Goodwill to all men, meaning, of course, all humans.

5
00:00:59,545 --> 00:01:02,271
And I'm sure you noticed my little sign on the gate.

6
00:01:03,612 --> 00:01:05,156
I've extended it to all beings.

7
00:01:08,602 --> 00:01:11,546
In the hope it might affect the local farmer.

8
00:01:13,510 --> 00:01:14,132
So...

9
00:01:16,441 --> 00:01:24,090
So you can hear that little dog, he keeps it in a cage with a concrete base and it's obviously quite unhappy, but what can you do?

10
00:01:25,992 --> 00:01:40,088
So, goodwill for me really translates the word metta, although I'm sure you've seen it translated as loving-kindness, which gives it its effective value, you know, its emotional value.

11
00:01:41,569 --> 00:01:46,296
But we have to link that really with the Buddha's teaching about karma.

12
00:01:46,849 --> 00:01:49,073
And karma is an action.

13
00:01:49,694 --> 00:01:53,182
I'm using the word technically now, not your comeuppance.

14
00:01:53,522 --> 00:01:54,685
You know, you get your karma.

15
00:01:55,566 --> 00:01:57,250
But more in the sense of just an action.

16
00:01:58,352 --> 00:02:05,144
And an action is driven by, the action is a point where the will comes in.

17
00:02:06,947 --> 00:02:19,604
And then with the will you have the action and the action of course produces the beginning of a conditioning or reinforces a present conditioning and that's your bhava, that's your becoming.

18
00:02:23,187 --> 00:02:30,777
Really it's just looking at the position that the Buddha puts this whole business of karma into his teachings.

19
00:02:33,543 --> 00:02:44,675
When he went through that liberation process he came out with what's known as the three knowledges, the three great understandings he had.

20
00:02:44,695 --> 00:02:49,481
The first one was a realization that he was completely purified of all these negative states.

21
00:02:51,485 --> 00:03:00,175
Later in his victory verse he says that he attained this unconditioned consciousness, asankhita-citta.

22
00:03:01,555 --> 00:03:05,060
But the other two are related to how he got there.

23
00:03:05,340 --> 00:03:10,348
The first is he saw all his past lives and saw how he arrived at this particular place.

24
00:03:11,049 --> 00:03:21,604
And then he was able to perceive beings moving from one realm to another, driven by the same force, by the same karmic force, by their will.

25
00:03:22,705 --> 00:03:29,395
And what was then just a personal law became a universal law for him.

26
00:03:29,855 --> 00:03:30,836
And from that

27
00:03:31,036 --> 00:03:39,460
Over time, he develops dependent origination, which is the whole psychology of how we create our conditionings.

28
00:03:41,295 --> 00:03:50,411
But also he points to the whole business of ethics.

29
00:03:51,652 --> 00:04:01,228
So ethics in its broadest meaning is basically our relationship, our relationship to each other as human beings, of course.

30
00:04:01,394 --> 00:04:08,626
to the animal world, to the world of nature, to the mineral world, to use an old medieval way of looking at things.

31
00:04:08,985 --> 00:04:13,212
So even rocks and stuff like that we have a relationship with.

32
00:04:14,215 --> 00:04:23,790
It might not be a very deeply affectionate one, but we have a relationship with the physicality of nature.

33
00:04:25,879 --> 00:04:37,915
And in the Noble Eightfold Path, you see, this comes into play because after we've had some insights, this has to translate itself into Right Attitude.

34
00:04:38,596 --> 00:04:48,310
And these attitudes, he names three of them within the Eightfold Path of selfishness to generosity,

35
00:04:48,745 --> 00:04:52,389
hatred towards love and cruelty towards compassion.

36
00:04:53,732 --> 00:05:00,440
But you can take any negativity and you can state its opposite as where we're moving towards.

37
00:05:01,802 --> 00:05:06,269
And of course that's a change in relationship and that's what we're talking about, a relationship.

38
00:05:07,290 --> 00:05:13,317
And this then expresses itself in right speech, right action and right livelihood.

39
00:05:14,716 --> 00:05:28,028
So, this ethics is most keenly expressed, you might say, in its little detail in the Vinaya for the monks, for the monastic life, the monks and nuns.

40
00:05:28,848 --> 00:05:37,956
Because here he's trying to set up an institution, a specific institution, which is to preserve the Dharma, and of course to help people become liberated.

41
00:05:38,918 --> 00:05:42,141
And he sees that as extremely important.

42
00:05:42,120 --> 00:05:50,430
And it's not as though he starts from a position of some ideal as to what the order will be.

43
00:05:50,471 --> 00:06:09,833
He follows the normal customs of the time, which was basically to use whatever cloth was about to create clothing, to live very simply in the forests, making your own little hut out of things, out of wood and leaves, banana leaves and stuff.

44
00:06:10,538 --> 00:06:14,024
And to eat what was given in a bowl.

45
00:06:14,884 --> 00:06:16,408
All these things were set.

46
00:06:17,408 --> 00:06:21,896
And what it tells us is that here's the basis of a spiritual life.

47
00:06:25,622 --> 00:06:27,286
We need shelter.

48
00:06:28,648 --> 00:06:30,471
We need clothing against the elements.

49
00:06:30,951 --> 00:06:32,795
We need food to keep the body healthy.

50
00:06:34,737 --> 00:06:36,040
And the fourth one was medicine.

51
00:06:37,031 --> 00:06:54,096
And when you look across the world and you see these people who don't have these basic requirements, what we actually understand from the Buddha's teaching is that they haven't even got the basis for spiritual practice.

52
00:06:55,173 --> 00:06:55,494
You see?

53
00:06:56,033 --> 00:07:02,964
So, in other words, Buddha's saying that in order to even begin the spiritual practice, you've got to feel safe.

54
00:07:03,346 --> 00:07:04,327
You've got to feel safe.

55
00:07:04,928 --> 00:07:15,324
If your mind is concerned about where you're going to get your next piece of bread, or how you're going to clothe yourself, or your children, and so on, then it's too...

56
00:07:15,305 --> 00:07:21,132
You can't begin this process of purifying the heart.

57
00:07:21,153 --> 00:07:31,526
Saint Francis had a similar experience when he gave up everything in a very Buddhistic way and sewed together these bits of sackcloth to create his first robe.

58
00:07:32,827 --> 00:07:36,833
He thought to go and live with the beggars, actually live in Rome with the beggars.

59
00:07:37,533 --> 00:07:40,958
But he found that they were a little immoral.

60
00:07:42,202 --> 00:07:46,487
quite happy to thieve, and the language, of course, and the whole thing.

61
00:07:47,728 --> 00:07:54,276
And he had this ideal that, in fact, if you were poor, you were necessarily closer to Jesus, closer to God.

62
00:07:54,797 --> 00:07:59,081
But in fact, what he found was that they were robbers and thieves.

63
00:07:59,122 --> 00:08:03,987
Probably one or two of them were saintly, but generally speaking, they weren't a crowd he wanted to mix with.

64
00:08:04,247 --> 00:08:05,069
And so he left them.

65
00:08:05,088 --> 00:08:09,814
He went off on his own back to where he was brought up, started again, you might say.

66
00:08:11,514 --> 00:08:25,389
So during this time, Christmas, we have this idea of goodwill to all beings.

67
00:08:26,786 --> 00:08:32,932
We then have this sort of problem about will itself, meaning some sort of choice.

68
00:08:34,014 --> 00:08:43,244
In the West we have this idea coming really from Christianity of some sort of free will.

69
00:08:44,365 --> 00:08:48,710
The ancients didn't have that sort of concept.

70
00:08:49,270 --> 00:08:55,376
They were, I think, more deterministic, that things were already determined, a fate.

71
00:08:55,356 --> 00:09:04,517
And that choice was really some sort of trick that human beings played on themselves.

72
00:09:04,998 --> 00:09:08,927
Because they had choice, they therefore had free will.

73
00:09:09,919 --> 00:09:21,275
These days you get these different arguments between those who believe in a deterministic idea of the world and those who believe that we do have some measure of free will.

74
00:09:22,437 --> 00:09:32,653
Now, in the Buddha's understanding, it's hard to talk about this complete free will.

75
00:09:33,798 --> 00:09:40,249
It really stems from the idea of the Christian relationship to God.

76
00:09:40,830 --> 00:09:44,476
So God has created us out of love.

77
00:09:45,398 --> 00:09:49,806
And a love which is determined by him is hardly satisfying.

78
00:09:50,005 --> 00:09:54,894
If you could create a dog and program it to love you, then...

79
00:09:55,684 --> 00:09:58,754
You'd have a hard time thinking that this dog really loves you.

80
00:09:59,316 --> 00:10:01,201
I mean, he's already been broken.

81
00:10:01,481 --> 00:10:09,626
So the idea of free love was that a person could actually choose to love or deny God.

82
00:10:09,961 --> 00:10:31,258
And that was the essential dignity of the human being and the essential, what would you call it, the essential oneness of the human being as opposed to God, you see.

83
00:10:31,457 --> 00:10:34,163
So he'd created something which was separate from him.

84
00:10:34,986 --> 00:10:40,953
and therefore the human being had to find this relationship.

85
00:10:46,841 --> 00:11:00,217
In the Buddha's teachings it's difficult to see this free will because everything starts from this position of ignorance, the position of we're living under a delusion.

86
00:11:01,057 --> 00:11:03,159
And this delusion is driving us.

87
00:11:04,701 --> 00:11:10,466
So its main manifestation is acquisitiveness, which turns into greed and all that sort of stuff.

88
00:11:11,126 --> 00:11:30,643
And the reason is that in that essential delusion as to who we are, there's this presumed understanding that we are what we appear to be, so human beings, with the body, mind, heart, and so on and so forth.

89
00:11:32,293 --> 00:11:37,240
But there is always somewhere in the back of our understanding the problem of death.

90
00:11:38,442 --> 00:11:46,490
All meaning to the self is in life, to the self that feels itself to be this psycho-physical organism.

91
00:11:48,232 --> 00:11:56,884
Death is meaningless because my whole effort is to try and enjoy life and make life meaningful for me.

92
00:11:57,015 --> 00:12:03,381
And I might extend that into some form of relationship that gives my life meaning.

93
00:12:03,922 --> 00:12:10,688
So you have a humanistic approach which is that my life has meaning when I'm helping others.

94
00:12:11,328 --> 00:12:24,260
So sometimes you'll get humanists who are just as self-negating, just as giving, just as generous, just as compassionate as anybody who would say they belong to a particular religion.

95
00:12:25,261 --> 00:12:26,482
And it gives their life meaning.

96
00:12:27,408 --> 00:12:38,761
But even so, there is this underlying, shall we say, despair, because it's all going to come to an end.

97
00:12:39,543 --> 00:12:49,855
And it's very difficult for somebody who sees death as being the end of everything that they aspire to, everything that is meaningful in life.

98
00:12:50,206 --> 00:12:53,530
to turn upon death and really look it straight in the face.

99
00:12:54,010 --> 00:12:59,678
So there's always this gentle pushing away of it, the denial of death.

100
00:13:03,423 --> 00:13:09,952
And what the Buddha is saying is that this essential delusion as to who we are

101
00:13:10,202 --> 00:13:23,756
is creating this underlying feeling of disjointedness, of not being actually completely at one with nature that we're embedded in.

102
00:13:24,091 --> 00:13:25,573
Because animals don't worry about that.

103
00:13:25,774 --> 00:13:34,308
Animals, as far as we know anyway, they're just happy to live the moment to moment because their minds don't really go beyond.

104
00:13:34,369 --> 00:13:38,777
They don't have that imaginative capacity to imagine their deaths.

105
00:13:39,498 --> 00:13:48,293
Not to say that they don't know when they're actually dying or being killed, but they don't have that existential fever that can descend upon us.

106
00:13:50,095 --> 00:14:02,870
So when you consider that we've got this underlying delusion which is trying to make sense of this life, then everything is driven by that force.

107
00:14:03,913 --> 00:14:16,609
So although on the surface of things, when you walk into Tesco's and you think, well, am I going to have, you know, choco biscuits or fig biscuits?

108
00:14:16,589 --> 00:14:18,432
And I think, well, this is choice.

109
00:14:19,232 --> 00:14:22,398
This is a wonderful thing I have in this society of choice.

110
00:14:22,618 --> 00:14:25,201
The governments keep going about this choice.

111
00:14:26,423 --> 00:14:32,974
But eventually, you tend to choose the one you like, the one you've established a decent relationship with.

112
00:14:32,994 --> 00:14:43,570
So even though we have this idea of choice, actually, when we finally make the choice and we ask ourselves, well, why did I make that choice?

113
00:14:43,590 --> 00:14:45,312
We find it's actually all conditioned.

114
00:14:45,293 --> 00:15:13,647
that we've actually got good reasons for doing it, which is another way of saying it's not been a free will choice, it's not as though free will stands somewhere outside my conditioning and is able to make this choice which has nothing to do with the conditioning that I have within my psychology.

115
00:15:15,600 --> 00:15:23,337
So when it comes to the path, and we're talking about the way to go, it's like going for a walk, isn't it?

116
00:15:23,557 --> 00:15:28,428
You set off for a walk and you already have your map, you know where you're going to go.

117
00:15:28,561 --> 00:15:37,653
And wherever you come to a fork in the place or where you come to a place where you don't recognize something, you don't have free will.

118
00:15:37,693 --> 00:15:41,440
You look at your map and you decide you're going to go this way.

119
00:15:41,559 --> 00:15:45,725
Now, you might make a mistake and end up in a...

120
00:15:45,706 --> 00:16:15,105
drowning in a lake but we'll leave that one aside presumably you can read the maps and even if you do start walking into marshy land you know you've come the wrong way so you come back on yourself so the path isn't so much one of choice but one of discernment isn't it you see and if we discern wrongly if we make the wrong choices then there are certain things that happen because of that wrong choice which and the world mirrors back to us what it is

121
00:16:16,333 --> 00:16:27,727
Now, when we talk about karma, remember, in the sense of that which is leading us to liberation, it's never something outside us.

122
00:16:28,328 --> 00:16:43,168
So, if, for instance, I find myself being fired from every job that I happen to get hold of, and I keep saying to myself, these people really don't understand me, you know, they're absolute fools and all this other stuff.

123
00:16:43,148 --> 00:16:50,198
then slowly but surely it might occur to me that maybe I'm the fool and not these people I've been calling the fool all my life.

124
00:16:51,221 --> 00:16:59,875
But until I make that sort of little bit of insight, the world keeps mirroring back to me, you know, exactly what I'm doing.

125
00:16:59,855 --> 00:17:21,188
So, but if I were to say that losing my job is my karma, then I'd be slightly off center, you see, because my real karma is the conditioning I have inside me, the conditioning which is creating this personality, these relationships, which continually find me dumped.

126
00:17:23,327 --> 00:17:41,808
If on the other hand, you know, take the opposite, if on the other hand I find myself constantly, you know, in situations which are creating happiness around me and joyfulness around me, then again that's mirroring back to me my relationship to the world.

127
00:17:43,240 --> 00:17:51,590
So when anything happens to us, you see, there is that business going on.

128
00:17:51,931 --> 00:17:56,116
That doesn't mean to say that other people's karma isn't affecting us.

129
00:17:56,517 --> 00:18:01,223
I mean, you know, the old adage that, you know, just because you're paranoid doesn't mean they're not after you.

130
00:18:02,605 --> 00:18:07,711
In other words, things happen to us, but it might not be specifically our fault.

131
00:18:07,972 --> 00:18:11,356
Somebody else is also dumping their stuff on us.

132
00:18:12,890 --> 00:18:15,453
And to sometimes distinguish that is very difficult.

133
00:18:15,513 --> 00:18:18,978
In fact, the closer the relationship is, the more difficult it is to discern that.

134
00:18:21,501 --> 00:18:33,417
So, when it comes to this goodwill to all beings, we're really always looking at our relationships.

135
00:18:33,438 --> 00:18:36,201
That's what it actually means, just what is our relationship.

136
00:18:37,242 --> 00:18:42,069
And when it comes to ecology,

137
00:18:43,180 --> 00:18:58,163
and the world and all that, and we have all these deniers and all that sort of stuff, we might say to ourselves, well, even if it isn't the overheating that's causing this, it would be better anyway to think it is just in case it is.

138
00:18:59,644 --> 00:19:00,165
You know what I mean?

139
00:19:02,630 --> 00:19:06,695
If it isn't, fine, then the world is just changing in its usual patterns.

140
00:19:07,096 --> 00:19:12,124
But if it happens to be this business of overheating, then maybe I ought to do something about it.

141
00:19:12,374 --> 00:19:22,311
So there was, you see, a meditator here who I asked about ecology and whatnot.

142
00:19:22,352 --> 00:19:26,339
Somehow it came up in the conversations that they took two baths a day.

143
00:19:26,921 --> 00:19:31,509
And I said, well, isn't that a bit ecologically vandalistic?

144
00:19:31,690 --> 00:19:36,238
And their reply was, well, nobody else is doing anything.

145
00:19:36,826 --> 00:19:54,664
So you can see how in this particular case this person was judging their particular ethical relationship to the world by other people and excusing what they obviously thought, because of their reply, was in fact ecological vandalism.

146
00:19:56,346 --> 00:20:02,292
Their excuse was because nobody else was doing it.

147
00:20:02,662 --> 00:20:09,594
When it comes to ecology and things like that, you see, our question is to ourselves, what am I doing about it?

148
00:20:10,935 --> 00:20:16,085
What is my responsibility within this particular situation I find myself in?

149
00:20:17,047 --> 00:20:27,285
So here, for instance, I've gone to all sorts of silly extents to try and cut down the amount of fuel we use to heat water.

150
00:20:27,265 --> 00:20:29,169
And some of them have been slightly ridiculous.

151
00:20:29,529 --> 00:20:39,809
That thing you're using now, which I bought, which was meant to be one of these super kettles that would keep water warm, turned out to be...

152
00:20:39,910 --> 00:20:45,882
I mean, that's why I've got that glove around it, that covering, because it was just letting off heat all over the place.

153
00:20:46,164 --> 00:20:57,711
My latest escapade, as you've noticed over the sink, is a hand washing thing, but actually that water which comes straight from the well, straight from the

154
00:20:58,888 --> 00:21:01,815
cold water system is perfectly drinkable.

155
00:21:02,256 --> 00:21:07,086
So if you ever want warm water, then you can take it straight from that.

156
00:21:07,887 --> 00:21:13,398
And this allowed me to cut down the heat in the tank itself, which I hope you've all forgiven me for.

157
00:21:14,040 --> 00:21:16,224
So that is basically just hand hot.

158
00:21:17,488 --> 00:21:18,289
It's not even that, is it?

159
00:21:18,329 --> 00:21:19,412
It's lukewarm.

160
00:21:19,392 --> 00:21:21,535
And then, which is all you need.

161
00:21:21,775 --> 00:21:23,656
You only need lukewarm water.

162
00:21:24,137 --> 00:21:31,226
So, I mean, I go back to my experience, you know, in the East where only the rich can have a hot shower.

163
00:21:31,487 --> 00:21:32,928
You just, you don't have hot showers.

164
00:21:32,948 --> 00:21:37,794
You don't, I mean, most people still shower at wells and it's always cold.

165
00:21:37,814 --> 00:21:40,978
Always, you know, mind you, of course, you're in the tropics, but even so.

166
00:21:43,304 --> 00:21:51,798
So one thing that we can look at is just, you know, what is our relationship to the material world?

167
00:21:52,580 --> 00:21:53,582
How much heat do we need?

168
00:21:53,623 --> 00:21:59,333
What sort of clothes are we wearing so that we don't have to have the central heating on, you know, so high?

169
00:22:00,394 --> 00:22:01,936
The food we eat.

170
00:22:02,759 --> 00:22:07,287
So you go back to your basics, you see, the food, the shelter, the clothing, you know.

171
00:22:08,566 --> 00:22:14,122
I mean these days with clothes being so cheap people have quite large wardrobes, you know.

172
00:22:15,886 --> 00:22:23,689
I'm now sort of getting to that age group where I can be like the Monty Python sketch where he says, you know, well in my day

173
00:22:25,406 --> 00:22:27,670
You know, we had leather for breakfast, things like that.

174
00:22:28,371 --> 00:22:42,009
But this whole explosion of material goods means that people don't have a sense of kindness towards things.

175
00:22:42,049 --> 00:22:46,757
They don't treasure anything because, well, if you break a cup, you're going to buy another one.

176
00:22:46,737 --> 00:22:53,346
But there was a time when you broke a cup, you've got to crack around the back of your head because that would cost money.

177
00:22:54,509 --> 00:22:58,374
So it's a case of re-establishing really the preciousness of things.

178
00:22:59,035 --> 00:23:14,077
And in the Japanese tea ceremony, which I know very little, the part of the conversation is to appreciate the actual vessels that you're using, which may be cracked and very old.

179
00:23:15,204 --> 00:23:30,221
And there was a lovely tale told by Suzuki, who wrote Then My Beginner's Mine, where when the monks go off and take water with them, they always reserve a bit to bring back, to pour back into the river that flows past the monastery.

180
00:23:31,281 --> 00:23:35,226
And it's that sort of relationship that I think we have to re-establish.

181
00:23:37,127 --> 00:23:39,711
I have a niece who works

182
00:23:41,412 --> 00:23:43,775
around ecology for schools.

183
00:23:43,815 --> 00:23:46,439
She sets up little projects for schools, a charity of such.

184
00:23:47,240 --> 00:23:54,529
And, you know, when I was asking about that, her reply to me about people and ecology was, people don't care.

185
00:23:55,511 --> 00:23:56,232
People don't care.

186
00:23:56,292 --> 00:23:59,416
And, you know, it's a sadness.

187
00:24:00,057 --> 00:24:06,686
And we watched a film that was done by a French ecologist.

188
00:24:07,448 --> 00:24:10,051
And there was this very, very moving scene where

189
00:24:10,993 --> 00:24:19,884
I think it's in Uganda where the hippos on this lake were being slaughtered by poachers.

190
00:24:20,644 --> 00:24:27,913
And all the fish in the lake lived off the hippopotamus poo.

191
00:24:29,194 --> 00:24:29,855
That's what they did.

192
00:24:29,875 --> 00:24:30,297
They lived.

193
00:24:30,336 --> 00:24:33,180
That's how the fish lived in the lake.

194
00:24:33,961 --> 00:24:39,027
And of course, as they killed these hippos, the fish stocks went down.

195
00:24:39,731 --> 00:24:59,935
And the man who was looking after it and he saw that a little gang of hippos had disappeared, he starts weeping, he starts crying because he's so distraught at the uncaring nature of these poachers and just the inability of the government or anybody to stop the slaughter.

196
00:25:02,058 --> 00:25:07,224
So it's a case really of, you know, just...

197
00:25:08,452 --> 00:25:10,656
thinking about our relationship to nature.

198
00:25:12,480 --> 00:25:17,848
When it comes to animals, the animal world you see, it's a similar sort of thing.

199
00:25:18,809 --> 00:25:27,826
And it's very difficult really to find products which don't use something from animals.

200
00:25:28,686 --> 00:25:34,056
And here I think you can get very sort of tight around things.

201
00:25:35,807 --> 00:25:46,915
Although the Buddha created, although the Buddha pointed out these rules about not harming living beings, they were never set to us as commandments, as thou shalt not.

202
00:25:46,997 --> 00:25:49,001
It wasn't to do with that.

203
00:25:49,041 --> 00:25:49,923
They're training rules.

204
00:25:50,003 --> 00:25:51,488
See Karpada.

205
00:25:51,468 --> 00:26:09,375
And you can't make an absolute law in a relative universe because, depending on time and place, human beings, if they want to stay alive, have to eat animals.

206
00:26:10,147 --> 00:26:16,577
I'm talking about people in deserts and people up in the icy parts of the world.

207
00:26:17,199 --> 00:26:27,194
So it's not as though we have to be particularly tight about that, but it's something that we could...

208
00:26:27,174 --> 00:26:34,143
think about and just ponder and just look at the food that we actually eat.

209
00:26:34,943 --> 00:26:41,291
The idea of having a vegetarian or two meals during the week seems to be taking on, seems to be catching on.

210
00:26:43,575 --> 00:26:49,382
But I think one of the problems is that when we move into that moral area, we become moralistic.

211
00:26:50,123 --> 00:26:56,170
So again, it's sort of not being too tight around these things and just working with the situation.

212
00:26:57,904 --> 00:27:02,573
So here myself and Martin had to make a big decision about Christmas.

213
00:27:04,056 --> 00:27:19,982
So as you know, the Trust has made a commitment to using less animal products if we can, but careful not to name it as veganism, because then that locks you into a particular ism.

214
00:27:20,544 --> 00:27:23,067
And that's not really where the Buddha was at.

215
00:27:23,150 --> 00:27:49,494
I remember talking to a German man who'd come to the monastery and he was very uptight about Buddhism, you know, he just didn't like Buddhismos, he just didn't like this word, you know, we should call it Buddhadhamma, because as soon as you enter into an ism, it's as though you can't, it's as though it becomes set in concrete, see.

216
00:27:49,474 --> 00:28:06,278
So, when we talk about not being involved in taking life unnecessarily, I think we always have to be careful not to get into that ism business, but take each situation as it comes.

217
00:28:07,920 --> 00:28:14,809
So, anyway, we decided that it was Christmas and we would have roast and use eggs to bind it.

218
00:28:14,910 --> 00:28:19,296
So, it's just one of those things we gave in to that.

219
00:28:20,321 --> 00:28:41,452
Now, when it comes to human beings, here we have a whole, you know, it becomes very complicated because, you know, we have all sorts of ways of behaving towards each other which are unhealthy and equally as many ways as we can which are healthy.

220
00:28:41,652 --> 00:28:49,131
And tomorrow we might go through the perfections, as they call the parami.

221
00:28:49,151 --> 00:28:58,192
But again, it's recognizing that other people are our teachers.

222
00:28:58,173 --> 00:29:00,940
That's one really very positive way of looking at it.

223
00:29:01,421 --> 00:29:13,853
So, when somebody is creating some negativity within us, it's pointing out where we may be stuck, where we are actually holding on to views and opinions.

224
00:29:14,895 --> 00:29:24,952
And it's a case of really doing that moment to moment vipassana.

225
00:29:25,453 --> 00:29:32,465
We see vipassana as being something that we sit and do as a practice, and that's true, that's not a problem.

226
00:29:32,445 --> 00:29:47,231
But to keep that awakenedness in us so that when we meet somebody and they're pressing buttons, we're right there with the inner turmoil.

227
00:29:47,616 --> 00:29:50,279
as it were, not to identify with it.

228
00:29:50,460 --> 00:29:56,247
This is the whole point, isn't it, of practicing vipassana, is to disidentify with what we're experiencing.

229
00:29:56,928 --> 00:30:07,500
So when anger comes within me, when I'm sitting and I've got a memory and some anger comes up, I'm sort of, as it were, just gently pushing it away from me to observe it.

230
00:30:07,900 --> 00:30:10,603
And in so doing, I realize it's not me, not mine.

231
00:30:11,983 --> 00:30:14,386
But then we, in day life, we tend to forget that.

232
00:30:14,928 --> 00:30:18,231
And as soon as anger comes up, well, I'm going to be angry to hell with it.

233
00:30:19,613 --> 00:30:27,603
But the whole idea, isn't it, is to remain with this sharp awakenedness so that as soon as I feel the first stirrings of irritation, I'm right there with it.

234
00:30:28,084 --> 00:30:28,364
You see?

235
00:30:29,144 --> 00:30:32,048
Now, I can override that.

236
00:30:32,068 --> 00:30:32,829
See, this is the point.

237
00:30:32,970 --> 00:30:35,393
I can override that with goodwill.

238
00:30:36,200 --> 00:30:43,711
And the measure of goodwill could be just a certain openness to the person, just to actually listen to what they're saying without this immediate reaction.

239
00:30:44,811 --> 00:30:49,638
And if I'm going to identify with something, then let me identify with goodwill.

240
00:30:50,580 --> 00:30:54,866
So now here we come to another, this whole business about the self.

241
00:30:56,669 --> 00:31:05,820
The Buddha, in his teachings, it's not about getting rid of the self.

242
00:31:05,840 --> 00:31:18,115
It's about creating, first of all, a self which is beautiful, a self which feels dignified, self-worthy and has a lot of self-esteem.

243
00:31:19,397 --> 00:31:23,502
And it's only when we feel that certainty within us

244
00:31:23,482 --> 00:31:28,907
that we can begin to go deeper and drop the idea of what a self might be.

245
00:31:29,868 --> 00:31:42,601
But all his teachings, if you go through it, is all about, at this ethical level, of moving away from negative states towards positive states, from darkness to light, as he would put it.

246
00:31:43,402 --> 00:31:49,827
There are some beings moving the other way, he says, but hopefully we're moving the right way, from darkness to light.

247
00:31:50,332 --> 00:31:58,480
And so the whole training, part of the training is the Eightfold Path, is right speech, right action, right livelihood.

248
00:31:59,040 --> 00:32:02,384
And what it's doing is it's creating this beautiful conditioning.

249
00:32:02,984 --> 00:32:14,256
And when I associate with that, when I say, well, you know, I am generous, you see, then it's creating within me this sense of self-esteem.

250
00:32:14,276 --> 00:32:18,921
When I've forgiven somebody and I feel the relief that comes with that,

251
00:32:18,901 --> 00:32:22,147
You know, I'm purifying my heart.

252
00:32:22,788 --> 00:32:39,643
When you're practicing metta and you're saying, may I be safe, may I be well, it doesn't matter whether we believe there's an ultimate I there or not, but all we're doing is creating these conditionings which eventually build up to make us feel good about ourselves.

253
00:32:40,753 --> 00:32:51,425
Now when we move into that meditation, the next stage is to investigate this sense of I.

254
00:32:54,128 --> 00:32:56,631
So it's a sort of parallel process.

255
00:32:56,771 --> 00:33:06,221
The process of insight and the process of ethical purity run together, you see.

256
00:33:06,353 --> 00:33:18,371
If we're very disturbed over something, we're going through a patch in our lives which is full of anxiety and anger and all that sort of stuff, then it's very difficult to separate from it.

257
00:33:19,231 --> 00:33:29,887
And even if we keep falling into these habits of getting angry and all that sort of stuff, at least we know that we've fallen into a place where we don't want to stay.

258
00:33:29,968 --> 00:33:32,090
This is the point, we don't want to stay there.

259
00:33:32,070 --> 00:33:38,497
Often people will get themselves into this horrible place and they keep churning at it.

260
00:33:38,817 --> 00:33:48,307
I remember Rob, who's our treasurer, he's a solicitor helping people through divorce and whatnot.

261
00:33:48,948 --> 00:33:57,276
And I remember saying to this man something along the lines of, you'll lose what you want.

262
00:33:57,415 --> 00:34:00,019
You're not going to win this case.

263
00:34:01,196 --> 00:34:03,922
And you're going to spend a lot of money, right?

264
00:34:05,324 --> 00:34:10,112
So his whole argument was, let it be, come to an agreement and let it go.

265
00:34:10,813 --> 00:34:19,188
But he was too caught up in this bitterness and hatred and he was going to go for it, even though it was actually completely illogical.

266
00:34:20,501 --> 00:34:22,264
And that's what we tend to do.

267
00:34:22,304 --> 00:34:29,114
We get ourselves into these, you know, these whirlpools of thought, you see.

268
00:34:29,153 --> 00:34:33,219
And it's impossible to step out of it for a lot of people.

269
00:34:33,320 --> 00:34:34,320
They're just caught up in it.

270
00:34:35,242 --> 00:34:46,358
There was another case just recently on the radio there of a man who had been tortured by the Japanese on that River Kwai business really, really badly.

271
00:34:48,059 --> 00:34:51,190
And his heart was just filled with hatred and just anger.

272
00:34:51,210 --> 00:34:54,340
It was there, undealt with within his heart.

273
00:34:54,943 --> 00:34:57,570
And his first marriage eventually broke up.

274
00:34:57,592 --> 00:35:00,380
And then later on in his life,

275
00:35:00,884 --> 00:35:08,978
perhaps late middle age, he's just on a train and he meets somebody and begins to talk to her.

276
00:35:09,760 --> 00:35:13,746
And this stuff begins to just flow outward.

277
00:35:14,467 --> 00:35:19,516
And he gets in touch with all this goo, all this horrible stuff inside him.

278
00:35:20,407 --> 00:35:33,221
And for some reason, I can't remember the details, he sees this article where this Japanese man, who was his torturer, has written an article in which he's asking for forgiveness and whatnot.

279
00:35:33,240 --> 00:35:37,606
So he determines to go and meet him in Japan and give him the old waffle.

280
00:35:39,146 --> 00:35:44,793
But as soon as the man walks in, he meets this Japanese man.

281
00:35:45,213 --> 00:35:48,896
He just goes down on his knees and begs him to forgive him.

282
00:35:49,331 --> 00:35:52,681
And it's like he can't do anything.

283
00:35:52,722 --> 00:35:57,856
The forgiveness just pours out of his heart and they become good friends.

284
00:35:58,681 --> 00:36:17,179
In his case, he was very lucky that the fellow who now regrets bitterly the way he made these other human beings suffer, actually had the opportunity to tell this victim how he felt about it now.

285
00:36:17,940 --> 00:36:26,628
If not, this man may very well have been still twisting in the little hell of his own making, just unable to forgive, unable to forgive.

286
00:36:28,820 --> 00:36:40,025
So what our practice is teaching us is that all this negativity is not me in the sense that I don't have to do that, I don't have to indulge it, I don't have to associate with it even.

287
00:36:40,606 --> 00:36:43,875
I can see it as just another mental state.

288
00:36:44,007 --> 00:36:58,282
And even if I'm caught out by it every so often, and I find myself murdering people and stuff like that, even so, I can then remind myself after the act, you know, you lost yourself there.

289
00:36:58,382 --> 00:37:02,666
There was a loss of myself into that.

290
00:37:03,487 --> 00:37:12,697
And if I can bring myself out of that and reestablish this good self, you see, then at least I'm not justifying the act.

291
00:37:13,184 --> 00:37:18,871
A lot of people might justify anger, righteous anger and all that sort of stuff.

292
00:37:21,155 --> 00:37:23,898
But in Buddhist terms, it's very difficult to justify anger.

293
00:37:24,519 --> 00:37:38,820
You can sublimate it, you can turn your anger into doing something, but anger itself, the feeling of anger, the hatred that's involved in it, as soon as you put that out, it's a negativity, it's a negative force.

294
00:37:38,800 --> 00:37:41,606
And it'll have its effect in one way or the other, you know.

295
00:37:42,246 --> 00:37:50,222
Even if you get your own way, you'll have got your own way, which may be perfectly just, at the expense of friendship, see.

296
00:37:50,704 --> 00:37:56,295
The person might do it just out of, you know, because you've hammered them, because they're so afraid of you.

297
00:37:56,715 --> 00:37:59,442
But that's hardly a good reason for them to do it.

298
00:38:01,784 --> 00:38:12,974
So what we're trying to do at the level of self, at the level of me feeling I am, I am this, I am that, is moving myself towards this better place.

299
00:38:13,275 --> 00:38:22,052
And when I get there, I find myself being more contented, less caught up in these mental states and so on and so forth.

300
00:38:22,293 --> 00:38:28,164
And this allows my meditation to go deeper because these are, in our meditation, what we call the hindrances.

301
00:38:28,405 --> 00:38:34,677
They're actually stopping us from going deeper and seeing where the initial problem lies, you see.

302
00:38:36,478 --> 00:38:44,835
So this goodwill that we are generally spreading around all over the place at Christmas,

303
00:38:46,773 --> 00:38:48,675
is something that we also need.

304
00:38:48,715 --> 00:38:53,159
It's not only an outward flow, it's an inward flow towards ourselves.

305
00:38:54,139 --> 00:39:01,867
And one of the purposes of practicing metta-bhāvanā is to get that feeling of self-worth about ourselves.

306
00:39:01,887 --> 00:39:13,539
So even during this time, it depends how you wish to spend tomorrow, but you might spend some time just reflecting.

307
00:39:13,519 --> 00:39:37,972
And just, you know, just try to guide your thoughts towards those areas where we find ourselves stuck or where we find certain irritations, etc., etc., certain fears, anxieties, and just see them that actually they're telling us something about ourselves, the situation out there, the person out there.

308
00:39:37,992 --> 00:39:43,019
And then just to find a way of allowing yourself

309
00:39:43,253 --> 00:39:46,699
that original fear, anger, whatever it is, to arise.

310
00:39:47,961 --> 00:40:02,248
And as it moves away, as it turns away, you see, to establish the right relationship, the right relationship with a situation or with a person and so on.

311
00:40:02,268 --> 00:40:04,653
So as we all know, this isn't easy work.

312
00:40:05,983 --> 00:40:07,965
You've got to keep at it.

313
00:40:08,746 --> 00:40:17,375
And even though sometimes you might feel things are going worse, sometimes it feels like that before it gets better.

314
00:40:17,534 --> 00:40:18,556
I'm sure you've heard that one before.

315
00:40:20,577 --> 00:40:25,101
So it's a case of really seeing our lives as an ethical process.

316
00:40:25,402 --> 00:40:29,826
It's not just this insightful process into impermanence and whatnot.

317
00:40:29,846 --> 00:40:31,447
It's actually an ethical process.

318
00:40:31,527 --> 00:40:34,050
It's a process of correcting our relationships.

319
00:40:35,431 --> 00:40:42,282
And in a sense that's looking at the third, this middle characteristic of dukkha, of suffering.

320
00:40:42,784 --> 00:40:45,548
And remember, it always comes down to desire.

321
00:40:46,210 --> 00:40:49,076
So this desire is a specific desire.

322
00:40:49,516 --> 00:40:52,862
It's not all desire, the desire to meditate, the desire to be liberated.

323
00:40:53,342 --> 00:40:54,965
It's not this tanha.

324
00:40:54,985 --> 00:40:58,231
This desire is always based on desire.

325
00:40:58,211 --> 00:41:05,001
some wrong relationship we have, see, which is a fundamental delusion about who we are.

326
00:41:05,400 --> 00:41:21,443
So, even when we turn towards things like, the ultimate things, like death, you know, you know, the Buddha's not shy about sort of hitting nails on their head, you know, like, life is uncertain, death is certain.

327
00:41:21,463 --> 00:41:26,329
I mean, that's, you know, like, he keeps sort of poking you in the eye, sort of wake you up.

328
00:41:26,815 --> 00:41:40,561
And it's being able to turn on that, you see, turn on that certainty and looking at that fear because right there at the very fear of death we find this self.

329
00:41:41,061 --> 00:41:49,396
It's the self, you see, it's this wrong relationship which is creating that initial, that deep, that deepest of all fears.

330
00:42:07,112 --> 00:42:20,215
So, just trying really to make that path quite clear to ourselves, that on the one side there's the process of insight, the process of seeing things as they really are, as the Buddha said.

331
00:42:20,255 --> 00:42:28,949
And on the other side, it's how it manifests in our daily actions, speech, actions and livelihood.

332
00:42:29,971 --> 00:42:32,715
And the one has to mirror the other.

333
00:42:35,277 --> 00:43:02,802
the way to liberation can come through any of those points on the Eightfold Path especially those points about right speech, right action but especially that right livelihood because in our actions we come across where the self is creating barriers where the self is not able to extend itself in a fluid way into a situation

334
00:43:05,163 --> 00:43:10,969
definitions, opinions, views, and all that sort of stuff, you see.

335
00:43:11,048 --> 00:43:28,788
Just as a final example of the distinction between what you might call a barrier and a boundary, see boundaries are fluid, using that word as a fluid thing, is this whole business about opinions and views.

336
00:43:29,447 --> 00:43:29,989
So,

337
00:43:31,706 --> 00:43:38,675
If we see an opinion as just a perspective on a particular situation, political, social, etc.

338
00:43:39,496 --> 00:43:45,706
If it's just a perspective, we're much more open to accepting that other people have different perspectives.

339
00:43:46,527 --> 00:43:50,311
And there's an ability there to work with it to find a compromise.

340
00:43:50,893 --> 00:43:57,481
So in terms of a self which is not so self-seeking, the word compromise is not a dirty word.

341
00:43:57,981 --> 00:44:01,646
But as soon as you identify with your opinion, I am...

342
00:44:01,626 --> 00:44:04,632
So it's very difficult to find that bridge.

343
00:44:05,512 --> 00:44:09,358
And we see it constantly in places like the Middle East.

344
00:44:10,661 --> 00:44:23,922
There doesn't seem to be a way that these two sides can even come close to some sort of compromise, some sort of way of understanding each other and giving each other the sense of freedom they want.

345
00:44:26,905 --> 00:44:31,291
However, it is Christmas, and we have to spread a bit of goodwill.

346
00:44:31,992 --> 00:44:38,099
And this evening in our Meta, perhaps we can bring these things to mind, like the Middle East, and send out our goodwill.

347
00:44:39,280 --> 00:44:40,722
Just another final thing.

348
00:44:41,463 --> 00:44:49,875
Some people doubt the power of prayer, you know, goodwill, blessings, and that sort of stuff.

349
00:44:49,855 --> 00:44:54,280
But there's a woman called Caroline Miss, some of you might have heard of.

350
00:44:54,300 --> 00:45:01,530
And she tells a tale of a car crash in which the woman dies, comes out of her body.

351
00:45:02,791 --> 00:45:09,380
And as she looks down the line of cars, all these people are swearing and getting very angry with her and all that sort of stuff.

352
00:45:09,400 --> 00:45:11,503
But there's one woman who's praying for her.

353
00:45:12,184 --> 00:45:16,469
And what she sees is this energy going up and then coming down upon her.

354
00:45:17,463 --> 00:45:21,391
Anyway, as it is, she didn't die and she goes back into the body and all that.

355
00:45:21,811 --> 00:45:28,264
But she remembers the number plate of this person and seeks her out and takes her a bunch of flowers.

356
00:45:29,007 --> 00:45:31,472
So...

357
00:45:31,688 --> 00:45:44,478
even though we might do Metta only to help recondition our own hearts towards what is goodwill, I don't think we should doubt that it has some force.

358
00:45:45,179 --> 00:45:48,567
I'm always bemused, really, because, as you know,

359
00:45:48,817 --> 00:45:54,985
We read out these names in the morning, and occasionally somebody will say it really helped.

360
00:45:55,666 --> 00:46:01,014
And I can't really understand how it did it, but they actually feel it.

361
00:46:01,434 --> 00:46:08,985
And there was one occasion, I mean, if you're a scientific materialist, obviously it's not going to make sense to you.

362
00:46:08,965 --> 00:46:22,385
But there was one case where somebody was dying and we were offering metta and it so happened they died during that period when we were offering metta, which I thought was extraordinary.

363
00:46:22,405 --> 00:46:25,829
Which means, I suppose you could translate that as being we killed them.

364
00:46:30,396 --> 00:46:35,023
But I think of it more positively as helping them move on.

365
00:46:39,222 --> 00:46:42,230
So anyway, I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

366
00:46:42,250 --> 00:46:52,637
May you be fully liberated by observing these twin parts of the path of insight and ethical relationships.

367
00:46:54,181 --> 00:47:03,407
Sooner rather than later.

